<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="multiple">
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,1399,1418,1479]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
As all known species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoffman" authorityYear="2005" box="[492,579,1419,1444]" class="Diplopoda" family="Gomphodesmidae" genus="Pogoro" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[492,579,1419,1444]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Pogoro</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
live in the Udzungwa Mts, they can be keyed out using the key to Udzungwa gomphodesmids above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,303,1518,1544]" box="[189,303,1518,1544]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1518,1544]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1518,1544]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,1399,1563,1761]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
All three species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoffman" authorityYear="2005" box="[416,503,1564,1589]" class="Diplopoda" family="Gomphodesmidae" genus="Pogoro" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[416,503,1564,1589]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Pogoro</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been collected within a relatively small area in the Udzungwa Scarp FR; the collecting sites are hardly more than 
<quantity box="[658,731,1597,1623]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="km" value="10.0">10 km</quantity>
apart (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Menegon M. &amp; Salvidio S." box="[849,1162,1597,1624]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="205 - 212" refId="ref12202" refString="Menegon M. &amp; Salvidio S. 2005. Amphibian and reptile diversity in the southern Udzungwa Scarp Forest Reserve, south-eastern Tanzania. In: Huber B. A., Sinclair B. J. &amp; Lampe K. - H. (eds) African Biodiversity: Molecules, Organisms, Ecosystems. Proceedings of the 5 th International Symposium of Tropical Biology, Museum Koenig, Bonn: 205 - 212. Springer Verlag, Boston. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 0 - 387 - 24320 - 8 _ 18" type="book chapter" year="2005">Menegon &amp; Salvidio 2005</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1). Considering that the species are very similar to each other, and that only one male specimen of each is known for two of them, the possibility that they all represent one variable species cannot be excluded. Additional collecting is needed to elucidate this, but for the time being we consider the differences mentioned in the key and description as warranting separate species status.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
